# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-chloroethanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] The chemical compound **1,2-dichloroethane**, commonly known as **ethylene dichloride** (**EDC**), is a chlorinated hydrocarbon.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] It is a colourless liquid with a chloroform-like odour.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] The most common use of 1,2-dichloroethane is in the production of vinyl chloride, which is used to make polyvinyl chloride (PVC) pipes, furniture and automobile upholstery, wall coverings, housewares, and automobile parts.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane is also used generally as an intermediate for other organic chemical compounds, and as a solvent.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] It forms azeotropes with many other solvents, including water (at a boiling point of 70.5 °C or 158.9 °F or 343.6 K) and other chlorocarbons.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Although the *Gezelschap* in practice did not do much in-depth scientific research, they and their publications were highly regarded.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Part of that acknowledgement is that 1,2-dichloroethane was called "Dutch oil" in old chemistry.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] This is also the origin of the archaic term "olefiant gas" (oil-making gas) for ethylene, for in this reaction it is ethylene that makes the Dutch oil.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] "Olefiant gas" is the etymological origin of the modern term "olefins", the family of hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the first member.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Nearly 20 million tons of 1,2-dichloroethane are produced annually in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Approximately 95% of the world's production of 1,2-dichloroethane is used in the production of vinyl chloride monomer (VCM) with hydrogen chloride as a byproduct.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] VCM is the precursor to polyvinyl chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] The hydrogen chloride can be re-used in the production of more 1,2-dichloroethane via the oxychlorination route described above.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane has been used as degreaser and paint remover but this use has phased out due to its toxicity.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] As a useful 'building block' reagent, it is used as an intermediate in the production of diverse organic compounds such as ethylenediamine and higher ethyleneamines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] In the laboratory it is occasionally used as a source of chlorine, with elimination of ethene and chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Via several steps, 1,2-dichloroethane is a precursor to 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Historically, before leaded petrol was phased out, chloroethanes were used as an additive in petrol to prevent lead buildup in engines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] It is also toxic (especially by inhalation due to its high vapour pressure) and possibly carcinogenic.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Its high solubility and 50-year half-life in anoxic aquifers make it a perennial pollutant and health risk that is very expensive to treat conventionally, requiring a method of bioremediation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] While the chemical is not used in consumer products manufactured in the U.S., a case was reported in 2009 of molded plastic consumer products (toys and holiday decorations) from China that released 1,2-dichloroethane into homes at levels high enough to produce cancer risk.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Substitutes are recommended and will vary according to application.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Dioxolane and toluene are possible substitutes as solvents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/1-2-dichloroethane] Dichloroethane is unstable in the presence of aluminium and, when moist, with zinc and iron.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] This application has been supplanted by the more economic direct oxidation of ethylene.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] Otherwise chloroethanol is still used in the production of pharmaceuticals, biocides, and plasticizers.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] Many of these applications entail its use in installing 2-hydroxyethyl groups.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] Several dyes are prepared by the alkylation of aniline derivatives with chloroethanol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] It is also used for manufacture of thiodiglycol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] It is a solvent for cellulose acetate and ethyl cellulose, textile printing dyes, in dewaxing, refining of rosin, extraction of pine lignin, and the cleaning of machines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] Chloroethanol is a metabolite in the degradation of 1,2-dichloroethane.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] The alcohol is then further oxidized via chloroacetaldehyde to chloroacetate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] This metabolic pathway is topical since billions of kilograms of 1,2-dichloroethane are processed annually as a precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] 2-Chloroethanol is toxic with an LD50 of 89 mg/kg in rats.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] Like most organochlorine compounds, chloroethanol releases hydrochloric acid and phosgene when burned.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] It is classified as an extremely hazardous substance in the United States as defined in Section 302 of the U.S.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act (42 U.S.C.
[src:2-chloroethanol/2-chloroethanol] 11002), and is subject to strict reporting requirements by facilities which produce, store, or use it in significant quantities.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In chemistry, an **alcohol** (from Arabic *al-kuḥl* 'the kohl') is a type of organic compound that carries at least one hydroxyl (−OH) functional group bound to a saturated carbon atom.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols range from the simple, like methanol and ethanol, to complex, like sugar alcohols and cholesterol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The presence of an OH group strongly modifies the properties of hydrocarbons, conferring hydrophilic (water-attracted) properties.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The OH group provides a site at which many reactions can occur.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The flammable nature of the exhalations of wine was already known to ancient natural philosophers such as Aristotle (384–322 BCE), Theophrastus (c.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] However, this did not immediately lead to the isolation of alcohol, even despite the development of more advanced distillation techniques in second- and third-century Roman Egypt.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] An important recognition, first found in one of the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (ninth century CE), was that by adding salt to boiling wine, which increases the wine's relative volatility, the flammability of the resulting vapors may be enhanced.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the twelfth century, recipes for the production of *aqua ardens* ("burning water", i.e., alcohol) by distilling wine with salt started to appear in a number of Latin works, and by the end of the thirteenth century, it had become a widely known substance among Western European chemists.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still, by which an alcohol purity of 90% could be obtained.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The medicinal properties of ethanol were studied by Arnald of Villanova (1240–1311 CE) and John of Rupescissa (c.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] 1310–1366), the latter of whom regarded it as a life-preserving substance able to prevent all diseases (the *aqua vitae* or "water of life", also called by John the *quintessence* of wine).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The word "alcohol" derives from the Arabic *kohl* (Arabic: الكحل, romanized: *al-kuḥl*), a powder used as an eyeliner.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The first part of the word (*al-*) is the Arabic definite article, equivalent to *the* in English.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The second part of the word (*kuḥl*) has several antecedents in Semitic languages, ultimately deriving from the Akkadian 𒎎𒋆𒁉𒍣𒁕 (*guḫlum*), meaning stibnite or antimony.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Like its antecedents in Arabic and older languages, the term *alcohol* was originally used for the very fine powder produced by the sublimation of the natural mineral stibnite to form antimony trisulfide Sb2S3.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] It was considered to be the essence or "spirit" of this mineral.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] It was used as an antiseptic, eyeliner, and cosmetic.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Later the meaning of alcohol was extended to distilled substances in general, and then narrowed again to ethanol, when "spirits" was a synonym for hard liquor.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Paracelsus and Libavius both used the term *alcohol* to denote a fine powder, the latter speaking of an *alcohol* derived from antimony.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] At the same time Paracelsus uses the word for a volatile liquid; *alcool* or *alcool vini* occurs often in his writings.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The 1657 *Lexicon Chymicum* by William Johnson glosses the word as "antimonium sive stibium." By extension, the word came to refer to any fluid obtained by distillation, including "alcohol of wine," the distilled essence of wine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Libavius in *Alchymia* (1594) refers to "vini alcohol vel vinum alcalisatum".
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The term *ethanol* was invented in 1892, blending "ethane" with the "-ol" ending of "alcohol", which was generalized as a libfix.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The term *alcohol* originally referred to the primary alcohol ethanol (ethyl alcohol), which is used as a drug and is the main alcohol present in alcoholic drinks.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* appears in the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) chemical name of all substances where the hydroxyl group is the functional group with the highest priority.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] When a higher priority group is present in the compound, the prefix *hydroxy-* is used in its IUPAC name.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* in non-IUPAC names (such as paracetamol or cholesterol) also typically indicates that the substance is an alcohol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] However, some compounds that contain hydroxyl functional groups have *trivial names* that do not include the suffix *-ol* or the prefix *hydroxy-*, e.g. the sugars glucose and sucrose.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] IUPAC nomenclature is used in scientific publications, and in writings where precise identification of the substance is important.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In naming simple alcohols, the name of the alkane chain loses the terminal *e* and adds the suffix *-ol*, *e.g.*, as in "ethanol" from the alkane chain name "ethane".
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] When necessary, the position of the hydroxyl group is indicated by a number between the alkane name and the *-ol*: propan-1-ol for CH3CH2CH2OH, propan-2-ol for CH3CH(OH)CH3.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] If a higher priority group is present (such as an aldehyde, ketone, or carboxylic acid), then the prefix *hydroxy-*is used, e.g., as in 1-hydroxy-2-propanone (CH3C(O)CH2OH).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Compounds having more than one hydroxy group are called polyols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] They are named using suffixes -diol, -triol, etc., following a list of the position numbers of the hydroxyl groups, as in propane-1,2-diol for CH3CH(OH)CH2OH (propylene glycol).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In cases where the hydroxy group is bonded to an sp2 carbon on an aromatic ring, the molecule is classified separately as a phenol and is named using the IUPAC rules for naming phenols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Phenols have distinct properties and are not classified as alcohols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In other less formal contexts, an alcohol is often called with the name of the corresponding alkyl group followed by the word "alcohol", e.g., methyl alcohol, ethyl alcohol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Propyl alcohol may be *n*-propyl alcohol or isopropyl alcohol, depending on whether the hydroxyl group is bonded to the end or middle carbon on the straight propane chain.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] As described under systematic naming, if another group on the molecule takes priority, the alcohol moiety is often indicated using the "hydroxy-" prefix.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In archaic nomenclature, alcohols can be named as derivatives of methanol using "-carbinol" as the ending.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] For instance, (CH3)3COH can be named trimethylcarbinol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols are then classified into primary, secondary (*sec-*, *s-*), and tertiary (*tert-*, *t-*), based upon the number of carbon atoms connected to the carbon atom that bears the hydroxyl functional group.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The respective numeric shorthands 1°, 2°, and 3° are sometimes used in informal settings.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The primary alcohols have general formulas RCH2OH.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest primary alcohol is methanol (CH3OH), for which R = H, and the next is ethanol, for which R = CH3, the methyl group.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary alcohols are those of the form RR'CHOH, the simplest of which is 2-propanol (R = R' = CH3).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] For the tertiary alcohols, the general form is RR'R"COH.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest example is *tert*-butanol (2-methylpropan-2-ol), for which each of R, R', and R" is CH3.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In these shorthands, R, R', and R" represent substituents, alkyl or other attached, generally organic groups.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols have a long history of myriad uses.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol is the most common industrial alcohol, with about 12 million tons/y produced in 1980.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The combined capacity of the other alcohols is about the same, distributed roughly equally.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] With respect to acute toxicity, simple alcohols have low acute toxicities.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Doses of several milliliters are tolerated.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] For pentanols, hexanols, octanols, and longer alcohols, LD50 range from 2–5 g/kg (rats, oral).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol and ethylene glycol are more toxic than other simple alcohols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Their metabolism is affected by the presence of ethanol, which has a higher affinity for liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In this way, methanol will be excreted intact in urine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In general, the hydroxyl group makes alcohols polar.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Those groups can form hydrogen bonds to one another and to most other compounds.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Owing to the presence of the polar OH alcohols are more water-soluble than simple hydrocarbons.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol, ethanol, and propanol are miscible in water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] 1-Butanol, with a four-carbon chain, is moderately soluble.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Because of hydrogen bonding, alcohols tend to have higher boiling points than comparable hydrocarbons and ethers.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The boiling point of the alcohol ethanol is 78.29 °C, compared to 69 °C for the hydrocarbon hexane, and 34.6 °C for diethyl ether.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols occur widely in nature, as derivatives of glucose such as cellulose and hemicellulose, and in phenols and their derivatives such as lignin.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Starting from biomass, 180 billion tons/y of complex carbohydrates (sugar polymers) are produced commercially (as of 2014).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many other alcohols are pervasive in organisms, as manifested in other sugars such as fructose and sucrose, in polyols such as glycerol, and in some amino acids such as serine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Simple alcohols like methanol, ethanol, and propanol occur in modest quantities in nature, and are industrially synthesized in large quantities for use as chemical precursors, fuels, and solvents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many alcohols are produced by hydroxylation, i.e., the installation of a hydroxy group using oxygen or a related oxidant.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Hydroxylation is the means by which the body processes many poisons, converting lipophilic compounds into hydrophilic derivatives that are more readily excreted.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Enzymes called hydroxylases and oxidases facilitate these conversions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many industrial alcohols, such as cyclohexanol for the production of nylon, are produced by hydroxylation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the Ziegler process, linear alcohols are produced from ethylene and triethylaluminium followed by oxidation and hydrolysis.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The process generates a range of alcohols that are separated by distillation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Many higher alcohols are produced by hydroformylation of alkenes followed by hydrogenation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Such processes give fatty alcohols, which are useful for detergents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Industry produces low-weight molecular alcohols (e.g. ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, and *tert*-butanol) through the acid-catalyzed hydration of alkenes, the latter typically from cracking fractions of distilled crude oil.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Two implementations are employed: the direct and indirect methods.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the indirect method, the alkene is converted to a sulfate ester, which is subsequently hydrolyzed.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The direct method eschews intermediates, instead using water to quench an intermediate carbocation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Less aggressive reagents suffice for vicinal difunctionalization.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In industry, the diol ethylene glycol forms when ethylene oxide is hydrolyzed.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the laboratory, sulfuric acid also catalyzes hydration of alkenes to secondary or tertiary alcohols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] More controllable net hydrations proceed in multiple steps, with a vicinally-functionalized intermediate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Thus oxymercuration initially forms an organomercury alcohol, which can then undergo reductive demetalation; and alkenes react with *N*-bromosuccinimide and water to form halohydrins.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In hydroboration-oxidation and the related Mukaiyama hydration, an alkene is hydrometalated, then oxidized.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Ethanol is obtained by fermentation of glucose (which is often obtained from starch) in the presence of yeast.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Like ethanol, butanol can be produced by fermentation processes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] *Saccharomyces* yeast are known to produce these higher alcohols at temperatures above 75 °F (24 °C).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The bacterium *Clostridium acetobutylicum* can feed on cellulose (also an alcohol) to produce butanol on an industrial scale.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alkyl halides react with aqueous NaOH or KOH to give alcohols in nucleophilic aliphatic substitution.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary and especially tertiary alkyl halides will give the elimination (alkene) product instead.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Grignard reagents react with carbonyl groups to give secondary and tertiary alcohols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Related reactions are the Barbier reaction and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Aldehydes or ketones are reduced with sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride (after an acidic workup).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Another reduction using aluminium isopropoxide is the Meerwein–Ponndorf–Verley reduction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation is the asymmetric reduction of β-keto-esters.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] With aqueous p*K*a values of around 16–19, alcohols are, in general, slightly weaker acids than water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] With strong bases such as sodium hydride or sodium they form salts called *alkoxides*, with the general formula RO−M+ (where R is an alkyl and M is a metal).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The acidity of alcohols is strongly affected by solvation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the gas phase, alcohols are more acidic than in water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In DMSO, alcohols (and water) have a p*K*a of around 29–32.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] As a consequence, alkoxides (and hydroxide) are powerful bases and nucleophiles (e.g., for the Williamson ether synthesis) in this solvent.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In particular, RO− or HO− in DMSO can be used to generate significant equilibrium concentrations of acetylide ions through the deprotonation of alkynes (see Favorskii reaction).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with hydrochloric acid to produce tertiary alkyl chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Primary and secondary alcohols are converted to the corresponding chlorides using thionyl chloride and various phosphorus chloride reagents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] In the Barton–McCombie deoxygenation an alcohol is deoxygenated to an alkane with tributyltin hydride or a trimethylborane-water complex in a radical substitution reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Meanwhile, the oxygen atom has lone pairs of nonbonded electrons that render it weakly basic in the presence of strong acids such as sulfuric acid.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Upon treatment with strong acids, alcohols undergo the E1 elimination reaction to produce alkenes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction, in general, obeys Zaytsev's rule, which states that the most stable (usually the most substituted) alkene is formed.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols are eliminated easily at just above room temperature, but primary alcohols require a higher temperature.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] A more controlled elimination reaction requires the formation of the xanthate ester.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with strong acids to generate carbocations.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction is related to their dehydration, e.g. isobutylene from *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] A special kind of dehydration reaction involves triphenylmethanol and especially its amine-substituted derivatives.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] When treated with acid, these alcohols lose water to give stable carbocations, which are commercial dyes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohol and carboxylic acids react in the so-called Fischer esterification.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Other types of ester are prepared in a similar manner−for example, tosyl (tosylate) esters are made by reaction of the alcohol with 4-toluenesulfonyl chloride in pyridine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alcohols (R−CH2OH) can be oxidized either to aldehydes (R−CHO) or to carboxylic acids (R−CO2H).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The oxidation of secondary alcohols (R1R2CH−OH) normally terminates at the ketone (R1R2C=O) stage.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols (R1R2R3C−OH) are resistant to oxidation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids normally proceeds via the corresponding aldehyde, which is transformed via an *aldehyde hydrate* (R−CH(OH)2) by reaction with water before it can be further oxidized to the carboxylic acid.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] Reagents useful for the transformation of primary alcohols to aldehydes are normally also suitable for the oxidation of secondary alcohols to ketones.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] These include Collins reagent and Dess–Martin periodinane.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids can be carried out using potassium permanganate or the Jones reagent.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Organochlorides such as trichloroethylene, tetrachloroethylene, dichloromethane and chloroform are commonly used as solvents and are referred to as "chlorinated solvents".
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Chlorination modifies the physical properties of hydrocarbons in several ways.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] These compounds are typically denser than water due to the higher atomic weight of chlorine versus hydrogen.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] They have higher boiling and melting points compared to related hydrocarbons.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Flammability reduces with increased chlorine substitution in hydrocarbons.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Aliphatic organochlorides are often alkylating agents as chlorine can act as a leaving group, which can result in cellular damage.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Many organochlorine compounds have been isolated from natural sources ranging from bacteria to humans (e.g 3-chlorotyrosine).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Chlorinated organic compounds are found in nearly every class of biomolecules and natural products including alkaloids, terpenes, amino acids, flavonoids, steroids, and fatty acids.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Dioxins, which are of particular concern to human and environmental health, are produced in the high temperature environment of forest fires and have been found in the preserved ashes of lightning-ignited fires that predate synthetic dioxins.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] In addition, a variety of simple chlorinated hydrocarbons including dichloromethane, chloroform, and carbon tetrachloride have been isolated from macroalgae.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] A majority of the chloromethane in the environment is produced naturally by microbial communities, forest fires, and volcanoes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The natural organochloride epibatidine, an alkaloid isolated from tree frogs, has potent analgesic effects and has stimulated research into new pain medication.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] However, because of its unacceptable therapeutic index, it is no longer a subject of research for potential therapeutic uses.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The frogs obtain epibatidine through their diet which is then sequestered into their skin.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Likely dietary sources are beetles, ants, mites, and flies.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkanes and aryl alkanes may be chlorinated under free radical conditions, with UV light.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] However, the extent of chlorination is difficult to control.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Aryl chlorides may be prepared by the Friedel–Crafts reaction, using chlorine and a Lewis acid catalyst.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The haloform reaction, using chlorine and sodium hydroxide, is also able to generate alkyl halides from methyl ketones, and related compounds.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Chlorine adds to the multiple bonds on alkenes and alkynes as well, giving di- or tetra-chloro compounds.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkenes react with hydrogen chloride (HCl) to give alkyl chlorides.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Secondary and tertiary alcohols react with hydrogen chloride to give the corresponding chlorides.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Called the Lucas reagent, this mixture was once used in qualitative organic analysis for classifying alcohols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] In the laboratory, thionyl chloride is especially convenient, because the byproducts are gaseous.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkyl chlorides are versatile building blocks in organic chemistry.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] While alkyl bromides and iodides are more reactive, alkyl chlorides tend to be less expensive and more readily available.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkyl chlorides readily undergo attack by nucleophiles.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Heating alkyl halides with sodium hydroxide or water gives alcohols.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Reaction with alkoxides or aryloxides give ethers in the Williamson ether synthesis; reaction with thiols give thioethers.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkyl chlorides readily react with amines to give substituted amines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkyl chlorides are substituted by softer halides such as the iodide in the Finkelstein reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Reaction with other pseudohalides such as azide, cyanide, and thiocyanate are possible as well.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] In the presence of a strong base, alkyl chlorides undergo dehydrohalogenation to give alkenes or alkynes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Alkyl chlorides react with magnesium to give Grignard reagents, transforming an electrophilic compound into a nucleophilic compound.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The Wurtz reaction reductively couples two alkyl halides to couple with sodium.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Some organochlorides (such as ethyl chloride) may be used as alkylating agents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Reductive dechlorination is rarely useful in chemical synthesis, but is a key step in the biodegradation of several organochlorine persistent pollutants.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The largest application of organochlorine chemistry is the production of vinyl chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The annual production in 1985 was around 13 million tons, almost all of which was converted into polyvinylchloride (PVC).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Most low molecular weight and liquid chlorinated hydrocarbons such as dichloromethane, chloroform, carbon tetrachloride, dichloroethylene, trichloroethylene, tetrachloroethylene, 1,2-Dichloroethane and hexachlorobutadiene are useful solvents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] These solvents tend to be relatively non-polar; they are therefore immiscible with water and effective in cleaning applications such as degreasing and dry cleaning for their ability to dissolve oils and grease.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] They are mostly nonflammable or have very low flammability.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Some, like carbon tetrachloride and 1,1,1-Trichloroethane have been phased out due to their toxicity or negative environmental impact (ozone depletion by 1,1,1-Trichloroethane).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The most important is dichloromethane, which is mainly used as a solvent.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Chloromethane is a precursor to chlorosilanes and silicones.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Historically significant (as an anaesthetic), but smaller in scale is chloroform, mainly a precursor to chlorodifluoromethane (CHClF2) and tetrafluoroethene which is used in the manufacture of Teflon.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] The two main groups of organochlorine insecticides are the DDT-type compounds and the chlorinated alicyclics.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Their mechanism of action differs slightly.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) were once commonly used electrical insulators and heat transfer agents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Their use has generally been phased out due to health concerns.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] PCBs were replaced by polybrominated diphenyl ethers (PBDEs), which bring similar toxicity and bioaccumulation concerns.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Some types of organochlorides have significant toxicity to plants or animals, including humans.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Dioxins, produced when organic matter is burned in the presence of chlorine, are persistent organic pollutants which pose dangers when they are released into the environment, as are some insecticides (such as DDT).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] For example, DDT, which was widely used to control insects in the mid-20th century, also accumulates in food chains, as do its metabolites DDE and DDD, and causes reproductive problems (e.g., eggshell thinning) in certain bird species.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] DDT also posed further issues to the environment as it is extremely mobile, traces even being found in Antarctica despite the chemical never being used there.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Some organochlorine compounds, such as sulfur mustards, nitrogen mustards, and Lewisite, are even used as chemical weapons due to their toxicity.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] However, the presence of a chlorine-carbon bond in an organic compound does not ensure toxicity.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] Some organochlorides are considered safe enough for consumption in foods and medicines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkyl-chloride] For example, peas and broad beans contain the natural chlorinated plant hormone 4-chloroindole-3-acetic acid (4-Cl-IAA); and the artificial sweetener sucralose (Splenda) is a common food additive.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The SN2 mechanism is not available for aryl substituents, where the trajectory to attack the carbon atom would be inside the ring.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Thus, only reactions catalyzed by organometallic catalysts are possible.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] C-alkylation is a process for the formation of carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The largest example of this takes place in the alkylation units of petrochemical plants, which convert low-molecular-weight alkenes into high octane gasoline components.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Electron-rich species such as phenols are also commonly alkylated to produce a variety of products; examples include linear alkylbenzenes used in the production of surfactants like LAS, or butylated phenols like BHT, which are used as antioxidants.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] This can be achieved using either acid catalysts like Amberlyst, or Lewis acids like aluminium.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] On a laboratory scale the Friedel–Crafts reaction uses alkyl halides, as these are often easier to handle than their corresponding alkenes, which tend to be gasses.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The reaction is catalysed by aluminium trichloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] This approach is rarely used industrially as alkyl halides are more expensive than alkenes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The rate of alkylation follows the order tertiary amine < secondary amine < primary amine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Typical alkylating agents are alkyl halides.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Industry often relies on green chemistry methods involving alkylation of amines with alcohols, the byproduct being water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Hydroamination is another green method for N-alkylation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] In the Menshutkin reaction, a tertiary amine is converted into a quaternary ammonium salt by reaction with an alkyl halide.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Similar reactions occur when tertiary phosphines are treated with alkyl halides, the products being phosphonium salts.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Thiols are readily alkylated to give thioethers via the thiol-ene reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The reaction is typically conducted in the presence of a base or using the conjugate base of the thiol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Thioethers undergo alkylation to give sulfonium ions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] When the alkylating agent is an alkyl halide, the conversion is called the Williamson ether synthesis.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alcohols are also good alkylating agents in the presence of suitable acid catalysts.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] For example, most methyl amines are prepared by alkylation of ammonia with methanol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The alkylation of phenols is particularly straightforward since it is subject to fewer competing reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] More complex alkylation of a alcohols and phenols involve ethoxylation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Ethylene oxide is the alkylating group in this reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] In the process called oxidative addition, low-valent metals often react with alkylating agents to give metal alkyls.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] This reaction is one step in the Cativa process for the synthesis of acetic acid from methyl iodide.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Many cross coupling reactions proceed via oxidative addition as well.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Electrophilic alkylating agents deliver the equivalent of an alkyl cation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alkyl halides are typical alkylating agents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Trimethyloxonium tetrafluoroborate and triethyloxonium tetrafluoroborate are particularly strong electrophiles due to their overt positive charge and an inert leaving group (dimethyl or diethyl ether).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Dimethyl sulfate is intermediate in electrophilicity.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Diazomethane is a popular methylating agent in the laboratory, but it is too hazardous (explosive gas with a high acute toxicity) to be employed on an industrial scale without special precautions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Use of diazomethane has been significantly reduced by the introduction of the safer and equivalent reagent trimethylsilyldiazomethane.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Electrophilic, soluble alkylating agents are often toxic and carcinogenic, due to their tendency to alkylate DNA.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] This mechanism of toxicity is relevant to the function of anti-cancer drugs in the form of alkylating antineoplastic agents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Some chemical weapons such as mustard gas (sulfide of dichloroethyl) function as alkylating agents.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alkylated DNA either does not coil or uncoil properly, or cannot be processed by information-decoding enzymes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Without functional DNA, the functioning of the cell ceases, leading to cell death.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Thus, these alkylating agents are cytotoxic.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Electrophilic alkylation uses Lewis acids and Brønsted acids, sometimes both.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Classically, Lewis acids, e.g., aluminium trichloride, are employed when the alkyl halide are used.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Brønsted acids are used when alkylating with olefins.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Typical catalysts are zeolites, i.e. solid acid catalysts, and sulfuric acid.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alkylation in biology causes DNA damage.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] It is the transfer of alkyl groups to the nitrogenous bases.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] It is caused by alkylating agents such as EMS (Ethyl methanesulfonate).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Bifunctional alkyl groups which have two alkyl groups in them cause cross linking in DNA.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alkylation damaged ring nitrogen bases are repaired via the base excision repair (BER) pathway.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Several commodity chemicals are produced by alkylation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Included are several fundamental benzene-based feedstocks such as ethylbenzene (precursor to styrene), cumene (precursor to phenol and acetone), linear alkylbenzene sulfonates (for detergents).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] In a conventional oil refinery, isobutane is alkylated with low-molecular-weight alkenes (primarily a mixture of propene and butene) in the presence of a Brønsted acid catalyst, which can include solid acids (zeolites).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The catalyst protonates the alkenes (propene, butene) to produce carbocations, which alkylate isobutane.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The product, called "alkylate", is composed of a mixture of high-octane, branched-chain paraffinic hydrocarbons (mostly isoheptane and isooctane).
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alkylate is a premium gasoline blending stock because it has exceptional antiknock properties and is clean burning.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Alkylate is also a key component of avgas.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] By combining fluid catalytic cracking, polymerization, and alkylation, refineries can obtain a gasoline yield of 70 percent.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] The widespread use of sulfuric acid and hydrofluoric acid in refineries poses significant environmental risks.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Ionic liquids are used in place of the older generation of strong Bronsted acids.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Complementing alkylation reactions are the reverse, dealkylations.
[src:2-chloroethanol/alkylation] Prevalent are demethylations, which are prevalent in biology, organic synthesis, and other areas, especially for methyl ethers and methyl amines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Relative to benzene, aniline is "electron-rich".
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] It thus participates more rapidly in electrophilic aromatic substitution reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Likewise, it is also prone to oxidation: while freshly purified aniline is an almost colorless oil, exposure to air results in gradual darkening to yellow or red, due to the formation of strongly colored, oxidized impurities.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline can be diazotized to give a diazonium salt, which can then undergo various nucleophilic substitution reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Like other amines, aniline is both a base (p*K*aH = 4.6) and a nucleophile, although less so than structurally similar aliphatic amines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Because an early source of the benzene from which they are derived was coal tar, aniline dyes are also called **coal tar dyes**.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In aniline, the C−N bond length is 1.41 Å, compared to the C−N bond length of 1.47 Å for cyclohexylamine, indicating partial π-bonding between C(aryl) and N.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The length of the chemical bond of C(aryl)−NH2 in anilines is highly sensitive to substituent effects.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The C−N bond length is 1.34 Å in 2,4,6-trinitroaniline vs 1.44 Å in 3-methylaniline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The amine group in anilines is slightly pyramidal.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The hybridization of nitrogen is describe somewhere between sp3 and sp2.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The lone pair of electrons on nitrogen have high p character.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The amino group in aniline is flatter (i.e., it is a "shallower pyramid") than that in an aliphatic amine, an effect attributed to conjugation of the lone pair with the aryl substituent.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Consistent with these factors, substituted anilines with electron donating groups are more pyramidalized, while those with electron withdrawing groups are more planar.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In the parent aniline, the lone pair is approximately 12% s character, corresponding to sp7.3 hybridization.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The pyramidalization angle between the C–N bond and the bisector of the H–N–H angle is 142.5°.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] For comparison, in more strongly pyramidal amine group in methylamine, this value is ~125°, while that of the amine group in formamide has an angle of 180°.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Industrial aniline production involves hydrogenation of nitrobenzene (typically at 200–300 °C) in the presence of metal catalysts: Approximately 4 million tonnes are produced annually.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Catalysts include nickel, copper, palladium, and platinum, and newer catalysts continue to be discovered.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The reduction of nitrobenzene to aniline was first performed by Nikolay Zinin in 1842, using sulfide salts (Zinin reaction).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The reduction of nitrobenzene to aniline was also performed as part of reductions by Antoine Béchamp in 1854, using iron as the reductant (Bechamp reduction).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] These stoichiometric routes remain useful for specialty anilines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline can alternatively be prepared from ammonia and phenol derived from the cumene process.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Many analogues and derivatives of aniline are known where the phenyl group is further substituted.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] These include toluidines, xylidines, chloroanilines, aminobenzoic acids, nitroanilines, and many others.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] They also are usually prepared by nitration of the substituted aromatic compounds followed by reduction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] For example, this approach is used to convert toluene into toluidines and chlorobenzene into 4-chloroaniline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Alternatively, using Buchwald-Hartwig coupling or Ullmann reaction approaches, aryl halides can be aminated with aqueous or gaseous ammonia.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The chemistry of aniline is rich because the compound has been cheaply available for many years.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Below are some classes of its reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The oxidation of aniline has been heavily investigated, and can result in reactions localized at nitrogen or more commonly results in the formation of new C-N bonds.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In alkaline solution, azobenzene results, whereas arsenic acid produces the violet-coloring matter violaniline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Chromic acid converts it into quinone, whereas chlorates, in the presence of certain metallic salts (especially of vanadium), give aniline black.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Hydrochloric acid and potassium chlorate give chloranil.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Potassium permanganate in neutral solution oxidizes it to nitrobenzene; in alkaline solution to azobenzene, ammonia, and oxalic acid; in acid solution to aniline black.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Hypochlorous acid gives 4-aminophenol and para-amino diphenylamine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Oxidation with persulfate affords a variety of polyanilines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] These polymers exhibit rich redox and acid-base properties.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Like phenols, aniline derivatives are highly susceptible to electrophilic substitution reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Its high reactivity reflects that it is an enamine, which enhances the electron-donating ability of the ring.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] For example, reaction of aniline with sulfuric acid at 180 °C produces sulfanilic acid, H2NC6H4SO3H.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] If bromine water is added to aniline, the bromine water is decolourised and a white precipitate of 2,4,6-tribromoaniline is formed.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The reaction to form 4-bromoaniline is to protect the amine with acetyl chloride, then hydrolyse back to reform aniline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The largest scale industrial reaction of aniline involves its alkylation with formaldehyde.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The resulting diamine is the precursor to 4,4'-MDI and related diisocyanates.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aromatic amines such as aniline are, in general, much weaker bases than aliphatic amines.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline reacts with strong acids to form the anilinium (or phenylammonium) ion (C6H5−NH+3).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Traditionally, the weak basicity of aniline is attributed to a combination of inductive effect from the more electronegative sp2 carbon and resonance effects, as the lone pair on the nitrogen is partially delocalized into the pi system of the benzene ring.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Missing in such an analysis is consideration of solvation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline is, for example, more basic than ammonia in the gas phase, but ten thousand times less so in aqueous solution.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline reacts with acyl chlorides such as acetyl chloride to give amides.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The amides formed from aniline are sometimes called anilides, for example CH3−C(=O)−NH−C6H5 is acetanilide.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] At high temperatures aniline and carboxylic acids react to give the anilides.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Boiled with carbon disulfide, it gives sulfocarbanilide (diphenylthiourea) (S=C(−NH−C6H5)2), which may be decomposed into phenyl isothiocyanate (C6H5−N=C=S), and triphenyl guanidine (C6H5−N=C(−NH−C6H5)2).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline and its ring-substituted derivatives react with nitrous acid to form diazonium salts.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] One example is benzenediazonium tetrafluoroborate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Through these intermediates, the amine group can be converted to a hydroxyl (−OH), cyanide (−CN), or halide group (−X, where X is a halogen) via Sandmeyer reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] This diazonium salt can also be reacted with NaNO2 and phenol to produce a dye known as benzeneazophenol, in a process called *coupling*.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The reaction of converting primary aromatic amine into diazonium salt is called diazotisation.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In this reaction primary aromatic amine is allowed to react with sodium nitrite and 2 moles of HCl, which is known as "ice cold mixture" because the temperature for the reaction was as low as 0.5 °C.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The benzene diazonium salt is formed as major product alongside the byproducts water and sodium chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] It reacts with nitrobenzene to produce phenazine in the Wohl–Aue reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Being a standard reagent in laboratories, aniline is used for many niche reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Its acetate is used in the aniline acetate test for carbohydrates, identifying pentoses by conversion to furfural.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] It is used to stain neural RNA blue in the Nissl stain.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In addition, aniline is the starting component in the production of diglycidyl aniline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Epichlorohydrin is the other main ingredient.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline is predominantly used for the preparation of methylenedianiline and related compounds by condensation with formaldehyde.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The diamines are condensed with phosgene to give methylene diphenyl diisocyanate, a precursor to urethane polymers.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Other uses include rubber processing chemicals (9%), herbicides (2%), and dyes and pigments (2%).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] As additives to rubber, aniline derivatives such as phenylenediamines and diphenylamine, are antioxidants.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Illustrative of the drugs prepared from aniline is paracetamol (acetaminophen, Tylenol).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The principal use of aniline in the dye industry is as a precursor to indigo, the blue of blue jeans.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline oil is also used for mushroom identification.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Kerrigan's 2016 Agaricus of North America P45: (Referring to Schaffer's reaction) "In fact I recommend switching to the following modified test.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Frank (1988) developed an alternative formulation in which aniline oil is combined with glacial acetic acid (GAA, essentially distilled vinegar) in a 50:50 solution.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] GAA is a much safer, less reactive acid.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] This single combined reagent is relatively stable over time.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] A single spot or line applied to the pileus (or other surface).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline was first isolated in 1826 by Otto Unverdorben by destructive distillation of indigo.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1834, Friedlieb Runge isolated a substance from coal tar that turned a beautiful blue color when treated with chloride of lime.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1840, Carl Julius Fritzsche (1808–1871) treated indigo with caustic potash and obtained an oil that he named *aniline*, after an indigo-yielding plant, anil (*Indigofera suffruticosa*).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1842, Nikolay Nikolaevich Zinin reduced nitrobenzene and obtained a base that he named *benzidam*.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1843, August Wilhelm von Hofmann showed that these were all the same substance, known thereafter as *phenylamine* or *aniline*.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1856, while trying to synthesise quinine, von Hofmann's student William Henry Perkin discovered mauveine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Mauveine quickly became a commercial dye.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Other synthetic dyes followed, such as fuchsin, safranin, and induline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] At the time of mauveine's discovery, aniline was expensive.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Soon thereafter, applying a method reported in 1854 by Antoine Béchamp, it was prepared "by the ton".
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The Béchamp reduction enabled the evolution of a massive dye industry in Germany.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Today, the name of BASF, originally *Badische Anilin- und Soda-Fabrik* (English: Baden Aniline and Soda Factory), now the largest chemical supplier, echoes the legacy of the synthetic dye industry, built via aniline dyes and extended via the related azo dyes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In the late 19th century, derivatives of aniline such as acetanilide and phenacetin emerged as analgesic drugs, with their cardiac-suppressive side effects often countered with caffeine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Also in the late 19th century, Ehrlich found that the aniline dye methylene blue works as an antimalarial drug.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] He hypothesized that dyes that selectively stain pathogens over tissue would prefentially harm pathogens, leading to his "magic bullet" concept.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Salvarsan's targeted microorganism, not yet recognized as a bacterium, was still thought to be a parasite, and medical bacteriologists, believing that bacteria were not susceptible to the chemotherapeutic approach, overlooked Alexander Fleming's report in 1928 on the effects of penicillin.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1932, Bayer sought medical applications of its dyes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] By the 1940s, over 500 related sulfa drugs were produced.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Medications in high demand during World War II (1939–45), these first *miracle drugs*, chemotherapy of wide effectiveness, propelled the American pharmaceutics industry.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] In 1939, at Oxford University, seeking an alternative to sulfa drugs, Howard Florey developed Fleming's penicillin into the first systemic antibiotic drug, penicillin G.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] (Gramicidin, developed by René Dubos at Rockefeller Institute in 1939, was the first antibiotic, yet its toxicity restricted it to topical use.) After World War II, Cornelius P.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Rhoads introduced the chemotherapeutic approach to cancer treatment.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Some early American rockets, such as the Aerobee and WAC Corporal, used a mixture of aniline and furfuryl alcohol as a fuel, with nitric acid as an oxidizer.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The combination is hypergolic, igniting on contact between fuel and oxidizer.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] It is also dense, and can be stored for extended periods.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline was later replaced by hydrazine.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline is toxic by inhalation of the vapour, ingestion, or percutaneous absorption.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The IARC lists it in Group 2A (*Probably carcinogenic to humans*), and it has specifically been linked to bladder cancer.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Aniline has been implicated as one possible cause of forest dieback.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Many methods exist for the detection of aniline.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Exposure of rats to aniline can elicit a response that is toxic to the spleen, including a tumorigenic response.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Rats exposed to aniline in drinking water, showed a significant increase in oxidative DNA damage to the spleen, detected as a 2.8-fold increase in 8-hydroxy-2'-deoxyguanosine (8-OHdG) in their DNA.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] Although the base excision repair pathway was also activated, its activity was not sufficient to prevent the accumulation of 8-OHdG.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aniline] The accumulation of oxidative DNA damages in the spleen following exposure to aniline may increase mutagenic events that underlie tumorigenesis.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] This temperature is required to supply the activation energy needed for combustion.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] The temperature at which a chemical ignites decreases as the pressure is decreased.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] Substances which spontaneously ignite in a normal atmosphere at naturally ambient temperatures are termed pyrophoric.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] Autoignition temperatures of liquid chemicals are typically measured using a 500-millilitre (18 imp fl oz; 17 US fl oz) flask placed in a temperature-controlled oven in accordance with the procedure described in ASTM E659.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] When measured for plastics, autoignition temperature can also be measured under elevated pressure and at 100% oxygen concentration.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] The resulting value is used as a predictor of viability for high-oxygen service.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] The main testing standard for this is ASTM G72.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] where *k* = thermal conductivity, *ρ* = density, and *c* = specific heat capacity of the material of interest, $T_{0}$ is the initial temperature of the material (or the temperature of the bulk material).
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] Temperatures vary widely in the literature and should only be used as estimates.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] Factors that may cause variation include partial pressure of oxygen, altitude, humidity, and amount of time required for ignition.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] Generally the autoignition temperature for hydrocarbon/air mixtures decreases with increasing molecular mass and increasing chain length.
[src:2-chloroethanol/autoignition-temperature] The autoignition temperature is also higher for branched-chain hydrocarbons than for straight-chain hydrocarbons.
